    "sub_topic": "Interpolation and extrapolation of data using Lagrange polynomials",
    "message_1": "A research laboratory needs to estimate the amount of a specific chemical compound in a sample. They have taken measurements at five different points and obtained the following data:\n\nx   | f(x)\n---|-----\n2   | 10\n4   | 20\n6   | 24\n8   | 32\n10 | 40\n\nUsing Lagrange polynomial interpolation, estimate the amount of the chemical compound when x = 5.5.",
    "message_2": "To estimate the amount of the chemical compound when x = 5.5 using Lagrange polynomial interpolation, we can use the following formula:\n\nP(x) = f(x0) * L0(x) + f(x1) * L1(x) + ... + f(xn) * Ln(x)\n\nwhere P(x) is the estimated value of the function at x, f(xi) are the given function values, and Li(x) are the Lagrange basis polynomials defined as:\n\nLi(x) = Π((x - xj) / (xi - xj)) for j = 0, 1, ..., n and j ≠ i\n\nGiven the data points:\n\nx   | f(x)\n---|-----\n2   | 10\n4   | 20\n6   | 24\n8   | 32\n10 | 40\n\nWe can calculate the Lagrange basis polynomials for x = 5.5:\n\nL0(5.5) = ((5.5 - 4) * (5.5 - 6) * (5.5 - 8) * (5.5 - 10)) / ((2 - 4) * (2 - 6) * (2 - 8) * (2 - 10)) = 0.0546875\nL1(5.5) = ((5.5 - 2) * (5.5 - 6) * (5.5 - 8) * (5.5 - 10)) / ((4 - 2) * (4 - 6) * (4 - 8) * (4 - 10)) = 0.6015625\nL2(5.5) = ((5.5 - 2) * (5.5 - 4) * (5.5 - 8) * (5.5 - 10)) / ((6 - 2) * (6 - 4) * (6 - 8) * (6 - 10)) = 0.2734375\nL3(5.5) = ((5.5 - 2) * (5.5 - 4) * (5.5 - 6) * (5.5 - 10)) / ((8 - 2) * (8 - 4) * (8 - 6) * (8 - 10)) = -0.1015625\nL4(5.5) = ((5.5 - 2) * (5.5 - 4) * (5.5 - 6) * (5.5 - 8)) / ((10 - 2) * (10 - 4) * (10 - 6) * (10 - 8)) = 0.0234375\n\nNow, we can calculate the estimated value P(5.5):\n\nP(5.5) = 10 * L0(5.5) + 20 * L1(5.5) + 24 * L2(5.5) + 32 * L3(5.5) + 40 * L4(5.5)\nP(5.5) = 10 * 0.0546875 + 20 * 0.6015625 + 24 * 0.2734375 + 32 * (-0.1015625) + 40 * 0.0234375\nP(5.5) = 0.546875 + 12.03125 + 6.5625 - 3.25 + 0.9375\nP(5.5) ≈ 16.828125\n\nSo, the estimated amount of the chemical compound when x = 5.5 is approximately 16.828125."
